Netflix Recommendation System¶

Introduction¶

I will be implementing a content-based movie/tv show recommender, meaning that content will be recommended based on a movie that a user has watched by finding content similar to it. My goal is to implement a simplistic version of Netflix's "Because You Watched [Name of Movie/TV Show]", where based on a particular movie or show that you watched, you are presented with several other movies or shows to watch.

The actual Netflix algorithm is much more complicated than the one that I will be creating. Netflix has access to your user data (for example: what time of day you watch, what devices you use, etc.) as well as every other users' data that allows them to identify patterns and use many more features than I have access to (4). More specifically, the "Because You Watched..." algorithm is able to take into account similarities in plots and characters that allows it to "look beyond genre" (2).

About the Dataset¶

The Netflix Movies and TV Shows dataset is from Kaggle and it includes the following columns of data:

Column Name Data Type Description
show_idUnique ID ID for every Movie / TV Show
typeIdentifier String A Movie or TV Show
title String Title of the Movie / TV Show
director String Director of the Movie
cast String Actors involved in the movie / show
country String Country where the movie / show was produced
date_added Date Date it was added on Netflix
release_year Int Actual Release year of the move / show
rating String TV Rating of the movie / show
duration String Total Duration - in minutes or number of seasons
listed_in String Genre
description String The summary description

# get top 3
def top_3(this_list):
    if len(this_list) > 3:
        return this_list[:3]
    else:
        return this_list

# convert to lowercase and strip whitespace
def clean_list(this_list):
    return [str.lower(i.replace(" ", "")) for i in this_list]

# convert comma-separated strings in dataframe to lists
features = ['director', 'cast', 'country', 'listed_in']
for feature in features:
    netflix_df[feature] = netflix_df[feature].str.split(', ')
    netflix_df[feature] = netflix_df[feature].apply(top_3)
    netflix_df[feature] = netflix_df[feature].apply(clean_list)

# Implement Cosine Similarity

# Helper Function: Dot Product
def dot_product(vector1, vector2):
    sums = 0
    for i in vector1:
        product = vector1[i] * vector2[i]
        sums += product
    return sums

# Helper Function: Magnitude of a Vector
def vector_mag(vector):
    sums = 0
    for i in vector:
        sums += i ** 2
    # return the square root of sums
    return sums ** (1/2)

# Helper function: Calculate the cosine similarity between two vectors
def cosine_sim_vect(vector1, vector2):
    # check that the sizes of the vectors are the same
    if (len(vector1) != len(vector2)):
        new_length = min(len(vector1), len(vector2))
        vector1 = vector1[:new_length]
        vector2 = vector2[:new_length]
    # compute dot product between the two vectors
    dotprod = dot_product(vector1, vector2)
    # find the magnitude of each vector
    mag1 = vector_mag(vector1)
    mag2 = vector_mag(vector2)

    return dotprod / (mag1 * mag2)
    
# Calculate cosine similairity between all vectors in the dataframe
def my_cosine_similarity(matrix1, matrix2):
    cos_sim_matrix = pd.DataFrame(columns=matrix1.columns)
    for row in matrix1.index:
        for row2 in matrix2.index:
            sim_vector = []
            sim_vector.append(cosine_sim_vect(matrix1.iloc[row], matrix2.iloc[row2]))
        cos_sim_matrix.append(sim_vector)
    return cos_sim_matrix

# Function that takes in movie title as input and outputs most similar movies
# Reference: Rounak Banik,'Recommender Systems in Python: Beginner Tutorial'
def get_recommendations(title, cosine_sim=cosine_sim):
    # Get the index of the movie that matches the title
    idx = indices[title]

    # Get the pairwsie similarity scores of all movies with that movie
    sim_scores = list(enumerate(cosine_sim[idx]))

    # Sort the movies based on the similarity scores
    sim_scores = sorted(sim_scores, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

    # Get the scores of the 10 most similar movies
    sim_scores = sim_scores[1:11]

    # Get the movie indices
    movie_indices = [i[0] for i in sim_scores]

    # Return the top 10 most similar movies
    return netflix_df['title'].iloc[movie_indices]
